To apply Newton's method to this system of nonlinear equations, we first need to find the Jacobian matrix of the system. Let $F(x, y) = (f_1(x, y), f_2(x, y))$, where $f_1(x, y) = x^3 + 3y - 10$ and $f_2(x, y) = 3x - \sin(y)$. The Jacobian matrix $J(x, y)$ is given by:

$$
J(x, y) = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial y} \\
\frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial y}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
3x^2 & 3 \\
3 & -\cos(y)
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we can apply Newton's method iteratively using the following formula:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x_{n+1} \\
y_{n+1}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
x_n \\
y_n
\end{bmatrix} - J(x_n, y_n)^{-1} F(x_n, y_n)
$$

We will start with an initial guess $(x_0, y_0) = (1, 1)$ and iterate until the difference between consecutive approximations is less than $10^{-4}$.

1st iteration:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x_1 \\
y_1
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
1
\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}
3 & 3 \\
3 & -\cos(1)
\end{bmatrix}^{-1} \begin{bmatrix}
-6 \\
2 - \sin(1)
\end{bmatrix} \approx \begin{bmatrix}
1.347 \\
1.091
\end{bmatrix}
$$

2nd iteration:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x_2 \\
y_2
\end{bmatrix} \approx \begin{bmatrix}
1.347 \\
1.091
\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}
(1.347)^2 & 3 \\
3 & -\cos(1.091)
\end{bmatrix}^{-1} \begin{bmatrix}
(1.347)^3 + 3(1.091) - 10 \\
3(1.347) - \sin(1.091)
\end{bmatrix} \approx \begin{bmatrix}
1.373 \\
1.057
\end{bmatrix}
$$

We can continue iterating until the difference between consecutive approximations is less than $10^{-4}$. After a few more iterations, we get:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{bmatrix} \approx \begin{bmatrix}
1.375 \\
1.053
\end{bmatrix}
$$

So, the values of $x$ and $y$ that satisfy the system of equations to an accuracy of $10^{-4}$ are approximately $x \approx 1.375$ and $y \approx 1.053$.
